				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drchandra" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1956625); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1956625&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610221962" alt="DrChandra" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1956625)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/drchandra" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1956625); return false;" >DrChandra</a></span> <span class="odate time_1502853231 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 Aug 2017 03:13</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3571651">
									

<p>I'm a tad confused. You've upvoted and positively commented on tales in this series before, but you don't like the hub? I think Mr.Wrong is right, and that you don't understand the different types of hubs.</p>
<p>Yes, I'm aware that there is a hub for Herman Fuller (and found it hard to believe that someone would think otherwise), but that's a hub for the entire GoI. This is for my tale series, and I am by no means the only author to create a hub for a tale series.</p>
<p>For instance, <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/wills-and-ways-hub">Wills and Ways</a> has its own hub, and this is in no way redundant with the <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/marshall-carter-and-dark-hub">MC&amp;D GoI hub</a>. I created this hub because I realized I was six tales in and still just calling it 'my Fuller series'. Everything on this hub is by me and shares a continuity, making it a distinct subset of The Circus.</p>
<p>I fully acknowledge I am not the first one to suggest that Herman is gone. Peppersghost did that, and as I said in the about section, I am just building on what PeppersGhost started. That's kind of what this whole community is about; sharing ideas and expanding on them.</p>
<p>I agree with Mr.Wrong when he says you should do a little more investigating before making assumptions about authors. If you click the history button at the bottom of any page you can see who created it and who's edited it. If you click any site members name and go to their profile page, you can see pretty much everything they've ever done on the site. I assure you, I have read every Herman Fuller skip and tale, in most cases multiple times, and I was honestly a little baffled that anyone would think I was unfamiliar with the Circus.</p>
<p>As for deletions, articles are deleted if they fall below -9 votes for a period of at least 24 hours, or if they violate the site's terms and services. If an article does not meet at least one of these conditions, I think it's a little rude to suggest it be deleted.</p>

							</div>

								
					
